==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Bowery
<hw>Bow"er*y</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Boweries</plw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[D. <ets>bouwerij</ets>.]</ety> <def>A farm
or plantation with its buildings.</def> <mark>[U. S. Hist.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The emigrants [in New York] were scattered on <qex>boweries</qex>
or plantations; and seeing the evils of this mode of living widely
apart, they were advised, in 1643 and 1646, by the Dutch authorities, to
gather into ⟦ldquo⟧villages, towns, and hamlets, as the English were in
the habit of doing.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bowery</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Bowery
<hw>Bow"er*y</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Characteristic of the street
called the <er>Bowery</er>, in New York city; swaggering;
flashy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

